<DOC><DOCNO> AP891129-0298 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 2113EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-PanAm-Miami 1stLd-Writethru f0299 11-29 0140</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pan Am-Miami, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0299,0143</SECOND><HEAD>Pan Am Seeks To Resume Miami-Madrid Service</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT name to ``Pam'' sted ``Pan.''</HEAD><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Pan American World Airways said Wednesday it hasfiled for a federal permit to resume non-stop service between Miamiand Madrid.   The application with the U.S. Department of Transportation ispart of Pan Am's expansion at Miami International Airport, where itoperates 86 daily arrivals and departures.   The Miami-Madrid route presently is served only by foreigncarriers, said Armand Arel, Pan Am managing director in Miami.   The application seeks daily non-stop service to begin May 1 withBoeing 747 aircraft. Pan Am operated a Miami-Madrid route from 1978to 1980, spokeswoman Pam Hanlon said.   The New York-based carrier plans to increase its daily Miamiarrivals and departures to 132 on Dec. 15.</TEXT></DOC>